1
00:00:01,761 --> 00:00:03,761
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

2
00:01:01,081 --> 00:01:02,321
Are you kidding me?

3
00:01:02,721 --> 00:01:04,281
KEVIN: Sir, we need to be moving out.

4
00:01:04,601 --> 00:01:07,321
-The plane is on standby.
-I say when the plane leaves, Kevin.

5
00:01:07,401 --> 00:01:08,601
What do you need, money?

6
00:01:08,761 --> 00:01:13,121
It's not the money, sir.
It's the logistics and the scale.

7
00:01:13,361 --> 00:01:15,641
It's too big, too complex.

8
00:01:15,961 --> 00:01:19,601
And, of course, the confidentiality,
it's potentially very exposing

9
00:01:19,921 --> 00:01:20,921
for all of us.

10
00:01:21,041 --> 00:01:23,041
But especially for you.

11
00:01:24,361 --> 00:01:25,521
Frankie,

12
00:01:27,121 --> 00:01:28,401
we're family, right?

13
00:01:29,521 --> 00:01:30,801
I mean, you're my...

14
00:01:34,161 --> 00:01:35,841
-What are you again?
-I'm your niece's wife, sir.

15
00:01:35,921 --> 00:01:38,201
Exactly. But you get things done.

16
00:01:38,281 --> 00:01:41,281
-(EXHALES SHARPLY)
-Now, this could destroy me for 2020.

17
00:01:41,361 --> 00:01:44,481
So make it disappear.

18
00:01:45,801 --> 00:01:47,121
I'm not sure I can.

19
00:01:48,481 --> 00:01:49,481
(DOOR OPENING)

20
00:01:50,841 --> 00:01:51,841
What?

21
00:01:52,241 --> 00:01:53,241
NAJIA: Hi.

22
00:01:54,561 --> 00:01:55,801
Thought I was the only one in.

23
00:01:57,041 --> 00:02:00,241
I just came in to check everything
was all right before we opened.

24
00:02:00,321 --> 00:02:01,481
Who the hell is this?

25
00:02:02,721 --> 00:02:06,801
I'm Najia. I... I didn't realise
that you were in here

26
00:02:06,921 --> 00:02:09,201
or here at all. Wow.

27
00:02:09,321 --> 00:02:10,961
I thought I told you to stay
on the door, Kevin.

28
00:02:11,041 --> 00:02:13,561
I came through the door to tell you
we had to leave, sir.

29
00:02:13,761 --> 00:02:15,081
Unbelievable.

30
00:02:15,161 --> 00:02:17,721
What, do you, uh,
work for me or something?

31
00:02:17,801 --> 00:02:19,641
Yes, I'll be the general manager.

32
00:02:19,801 --> 00:02:21,401
Er, I thought while we were finalising

33
00:02:21,481 --> 00:02:24,081
I'd come in and familiarise myself so I
can hit the ground running

34
00:02:24,161 --> 00:02:26,001
-when we officially open.
-You're fired.

35
00:02:26,561 --> 00:02:27,681
Pardon?

36
00:02:28,561 --> 00:02:30,241
You're fired. Get out.

37
00:02:30,481 --> 00:02:33,321
-I'm so sorry.
-You have one hour

38
00:02:33,401 --> 00:02:35,561
to tell me how you're gonna
make this all go away.

39
00:02:36,801 --> 00:02:37,801
Okay?

40
00:02:38,961 --> 00:02:41,001
Kevin, I say when we go.

41
00:03:00,401 --> 00:03:01,681
-(GRAHAM GROANS)
-We're nearly there.

42
00:03:01,761 --> 00:03:03,281
-(PANTING)
-(STEAM HISSING)

43
00:03:05,161 --> 00:03:06,801
Are you sure you've got this
under control?

44
00:03:06,881 --> 00:03:09,201
-(YASMIN GASPING)
-Totally. New systems.

45
00:03:10,281 --> 00:03:11,681
Just running them in.

46
00:03:20,241 --> 00:03:22,041
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

47
00:03:32,721 --> 00:03:33,721
We're home.

48
00:03:34,521 --> 00:03:36,001
We're actually home!

49
00:03:36,081 --> 00:03:37,361
(GASPS)

50
00:03:37,441 --> 00:03:40,401
Yes! Result. See? I told you I'd do it.

51
00:03:40,801 --> 00:03:42,321
We're at Park Hill.

52
00:03:42,401 --> 00:03:45,481
-That's my flat, there.
-What, you live at Park Hill?

53
00:03:45,561 --> 00:03:46,601
We're just up there.

54
00:03:46,801 --> 00:03:48,321
YASMIN: And I've got
a mobile signal again.

55
00:03:49,761 --> 00:03:51,241
But no messages.

56
00:03:51,321 --> 00:03:53,761
But, to be fair, it's only half an hour
since you left.

57
00:03:54,361 --> 00:03:56,601
What, half an hour since we were
with you in that warehouse?

58
00:03:56,881 --> 00:03:57,881
Yeah.

59
00:03:58,521 --> 00:03:59,641
Wow.

60
00:04:00,081 --> 00:04:01,801
(INHALES) So...

61
00:04:03,041 --> 00:04:04,241
(SMACKS LIPS)

62
00:04:04,801 --> 00:04:05,921
I suppose this is it.

63
00:04:09,161 --> 00:04:10,161
Yeah, I suppose it is.

64
00:04:11,201 --> 00:04:12,921
Got you back. Guess we're done.

65
00:04:13,921 --> 00:04:15,121
Nice having you aboard.

66
00:04:16,201 --> 00:04:17,241
Thanks, Doc.

67
00:04:17,601 --> 00:04:19,081
It's been a blast, truly.

68
00:04:20,041 --> 00:04:21,281
Pleasure.

69
00:04:23,001 --> 00:04:24,321
What are you gonna do now?

70
00:04:24,921 --> 00:04:27,841
Oh, you know, back in the box.

71
00:04:28,521 --> 00:04:30,841
-There's loads to see.
-By yourself?

72
00:04:33,481 --> 00:04:34,761
Yeah, I suppose.

73
00:04:38,601 --> 00:04:40,241
-Do you want to come for tea at mine?
-Definitely!

74
00:04:41,321 --> 00:04:43,441
Yes, I would. Thanks. I love tea.

75
00:04:43,641 --> 00:04:45,281
Tea at Yaz's? Amazing!

76
00:04:46,001 --> 00:04:48,041
Are you coming?
Are we all going for tea at Yaz's?

77
00:04:48,841 --> 00:04:50,001
She didn't invite us.

78
00:04:50,441 --> 00:04:52,801
Don't be daft. Of course you're invited.

79
00:04:53,481 --> 00:04:55,121
All right, then. (CHUCKLES)

80
00:04:56,721 --> 00:04:57,721
Graham?

81
00:04:59,361 --> 00:05:01,561
I think I'll nip home first, Yaz.

82
00:05:01,681 --> 00:05:03,881
Maybe join you later,
if that's all right.

83
00:05:07,841 --> 00:05:09,161
Shall I come with you?

84
00:05:10,841 --> 00:05:12,201
I'd rather do it alone.

85
00:05:16,201 --> 00:05:17,681
Don't go without saying goodbye.

86
00:05:21,281 --> 00:05:24,681
DOCTOR: Tea at Yaz's.
Never been for tea at Yaz's!

87
00:05:26,561 --> 00:05:27,801
(KNOCKING)

88
00:05:27,881 --> 00:05:29,481
RYAN: I can't believe you live here.

89
00:05:29,561 --> 00:05:30,881
Anna!

90
00:05:31,001 --> 00:05:32,841
RYAN: I can see this block
from my window.

91
00:05:32,961 --> 00:05:34,081
(SIGHS DEEPLY)

92
00:05:34,601 --> 00:05:36,721
Almost neighbours all this time.

93
00:05:37,361 --> 00:05:38,601
I know.

94
00:05:38,961 --> 00:05:40,641
-It's cool.
-Yeah.

95
00:05:42,601 --> 00:05:45,001
-DOCTOR: Everything all right?
-Fine, thanks.

96
00:05:46,081 --> 00:05:48,441
Anna, it's Jade McIntyre.

97
00:05:48,521 --> 00:05:50,641
I'm outside your front door. Are you in?

98
00:05:50,721 --> 00:05:53,481
I'm home.
Got a couple of mates with me.

99
00:05:54,961 --> 00:05:56,201
Probably all out.

100
00:05:56,281 --> 00:05:57,561
You brought friends back?

101
00:05:57,961 --> 00:06:00,801
Sonya, Yaz has brought friends back!

102
00:06:00,921 --> 00:06:02,041
I'm getting food.

103
00:06:03,041 --> 00:06:05,201
What, you actually have friends?

104
00:06:05,281 --> 00:06:06,681
Is she paying you?

105
00:06:07,521 --> 00:06:08,561
(LAUGHS)

106
00:06:09,321 --> 00:06:10,961
Oh, look at your views!

107
00:06:11,601 --> 00:06:12,601
Never had a flat.

108
00:06:12,681 --> 00:06:14,441
I should get one. I'd be good in a flat.

109
00:06:14,601 --> 00:06:17,041
I could get a sofa.
Imagine me with a sofa.

110
00:06:17,121 --> 00:06:20,801
Like, my own sofa. I could get a...
A purple one, and sit on it.

111
00:06:22,001 --> 00:06:23,761
-Am I being weird?
-A little bit, yeah.

112
00:06:24,041 --> 00:06:26,521
I'm trying to do small talk.
I thought I was doing quite well.

113
00:06:26,681 --> 00:06:27,801
Needs work.

114
00:06:28,401 --> 00:06:29,601
Maybe I'm nervous.

115
00:06:29,921 --> 00:06:32,561
Or just socially awkward.
I'm still figuring myself out.

116
00:06:35,241 --> 00:06:39,081
You really like junk.
Are you collecting it, like stamps?

117
00:06:39,161 --> 00:06:42,281
-Ah, let me tell you about this mess.
-Don't get him started.

118
00:06:42,361 --> 00:06:44,401
YASMIN: Dad, we keep telling you,
stop picking it up.

119
00:06:44,561 --> 00:06:47,121
Mum's gonna go crazy when she sees
you've brought it home again.

120
00:06:47,201 --> 00:06:48,401
It stinks!

121
00:06:48,881 --> 00:06:51,161
-I can't just leave it there.
-Why do we have to have it?

122
00:06:51,241 --> 00:06:52,321
Well, I thought, maybe

123
00:06:52,401 --> 00:06:54,281
-as your sister is a policewoman...
-Police officer.

124
00:06:54,361 --> 00:06:56,441
And she said
she'd do something about it.

125
00:06:56,521 --> 00:06:58,001
I did, and they're looking into it.

126
00:06:58,081 --> 00:07:00,241
Well, not fast enough. It's a disgrace.

127
00:07:00,321 --> 00:07:02,481
Don't keep it in the kitchen.
Put it down the chute.

128
00:07:02,641 --> 00:07:05,801
It's evidence, and you know what
it's evidence of.

129
00:07:05,961 --> 00:07:07,121
BOTH: A conspiracy.

130
00:07:07,241 --> 00:07:09,321
Exactly, a total conspiracy!

131
00:07:09,481 --> 00:07:10,681
And getting worse.

132
00:07:10,841 --> 00:07:12,601
(GASPS) I love a conspiracy.

133
00:07:15,121 --> 00:07:17,081
-So, are you and Yaz...
-Mates.

134
00:07:17,721 --> 00:07:19,521
We were at primary school together.

135
00:07:20,001 --> 00:07:21,001
Just mates, then?

136
00:07:21,361 --> 00:07:22,361
Yeah.

137
00:07:22,441 --> 00:07:23,801
-That's good.
-(MOBILE RINGING FAINTLY)

138
00:07:25,081 --> 00:07:27,161
(MOBILE RINGING)

139
00:07:27,241 --> 00:07:28,281
-Hi, Mum?
-NAJIA: (ON PHONE) Hey.

140
00:07:28,361 --> 00:07:30,361
-Can you pick me up from work?
-YASMIN: What?

141
00:07:30,761 --> 00:07:33,121
-Now? Er, I'm just in the middle of...
-NAJIA: Yes. Now.

142
00:07:33,681 --> 00:07:34,761
It's urgent.

143
00:07:34,961 --> 00:07:36,241
I'll text you the address.

144
00:07:37,281 --> 00:07:39,161
Don't let on to your dad.

145
00:07:39,481 --> 00:07:40,841
I'll tell you everything when I see you.

146
00:07:40,921 --> 00:07:42,921
-Fine.
-NAIA. Thanks, sweetheart.

147
00:07:44,521 --> 00:07:46,481
-(MOBILE BEEPS)
-(SIGHS)

148
00:07:48,881 --> 00:07:50,041
MR KHAN: Is she all right?

149
00:07:50,481 --> 00:07:52,561
Yeah, she forgot something.

150
00:07:53,001 --> 00:07:54,601
Asked if I'd drop it at work for her.

151
00:07:56,721 --> 00:07:58,921
She's got a new job, posh hotel opening.

152
00:07:59,081 --> 00:08:00,961
Er, do you mind if I nip out quickly?

153
00:08:01,041 --> 00:08:03,601
-Need any company?
-Nah. I'll be fine.

154
00:08:03,801 --> 00:08:05,481
Er, we'll look after your friends.

155
00:08:05,601 --> 00:08:08,041
-I'm gonna make pakora.
-Dad, don't.

156
00:08:09,721 --> 00:08:11,121
He's terrible at pakora.

157
00:08:11,201 --> 00:08:13,721
MR KHAN: We never meet your friends!
She never brings anyone around.

158
00:08:13,801 --> 00:08:14,801
Married to the job.

159
00:08:14,881 --> 00:08:16,801
At least I've got a job
to be married to.

160
00:08:16,961 --> 00:08:18,601
-Bye.
-Hope you don't crash.

161
00:08:18,721 --> 00:08:19,881
MR KHAN: Girls, now.

162
00:08:20,001 --> 00:08:21,401
Sisters.

163
00:08:21,481 --> 00:08:23,961
I used to have sisters.
I used to be a sister

164
00:08:24,121 --> 00:08:25,361
in an aqua hospital.

165
00:08:25,561 --> 00:08:29,441
It actually turned out to be a training
camp for the Quiston Calcium Assassins.

166
00:08:29,521 --> 00:08:30,721
Going off on one again.

167
00:08:30,801 --> 00:08:32,921
Ooh, you've got a parcel to pick up,
left with a neighbour.

168
00:08:33,401 --> 00:08:35,161
Yeah, I've been trying
to get that for days.

169
00:08:35,361 --> 00:08:37,121
A couple of doors down. No reply.

170
00:08:37,201 --> 00:08:39,361
Do you want me to go get it
while you make your terrible pakora?

171
00:08:51,761 --> 00:08:52,761
(SIGHS)

172
00:08:54,001 --> 00:08:56,201
(KEYS JINGLING)

173
00:09:08,201 --> 00:09:10,041
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

174
00:09:10,121 --> 00:09:12,561
You'll have to learn how to change
the hoover bag now.

175
00:09:13,961 --> 00:09:16,441
And work out where I kept the spares.

176
00:09:18,001 --> 00:09:19,641
Rubbish collection is every Friday.

177
00:09:20,961 --> 00:09:22,601
Recycling, every other week.

178
00:09:23,401 --> 00:09:24,681
I know.

179
00:09:27,521 --> 00:09:29,041
I know.

180
00:09:30,201 --> 00:09:31,641
I've got so much to tell you.

181
00:09:42,241 --> 00:09:43,241
DOCTOR: No word from Graham?

182
00:09:43,401 --> 00:09:44,961
Do you think I should have
gone with him?

183
00:09:45,041 --> 00:09:46,881
-You know him better than me.
-Not much.

184
00:09:47,481 --> 00:09:48,481
Still no answer?

185
00:09:48,681 --> 00:09:50,761
We've got a package to pick up
for number 34.

186
00:09:50,841 --> 00:09:52,641
Think she took it in.
Are you a friend?

187
00:09:52,881 --> 00:09:56,401
We work together at the uni.
She hasn't been in for a few days.

188
00:09:56,481 --> 00:09:59,081
Didn't call in sick,
isn't answering her messages.

189
00:09:59,681 --> 00:10:01,641
Thought I'd drop by,
see if she's okay.

190
00:10:02,681 --> 00:10:04,361
-I'm Jade.
-I'm Ryan.

191
00:10:04,961 --> 00:10:07,241
-That's the Doctor.
-DOCTOR: Hello, Anna?

192
00:10:07,721 --> 00:10:09,961
It's next door but one.
Have you got a parcel for us?

193
00:10:11,441 --> 00:10:12,441
Mmm.

194
00:10:13,241 --> 00:10:15,041
I mean,

195
00:10:15,121 --> 00:10:16,841
-I could open the door.
-Mmm.

196
00:10:16,921 --> 00:10:18,481
What, like, break it in?

197
00:10:18,601 --> 00:10:20,601
No, just sort the lock.

198
00:10:20,961 --> 00:10:22,241
If you thought it was appropriate.

199
00:10:23,041 --> 00:10:25,081
If you're worried about her.

200
00:10:25,601 --> 00:10:26,601
I am.

201
00:10:28,761 --> 00:10:30,201
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)
-(DOOR UNLOCKS)

202
00:10:30,641 --> 00:10:31,961
DOCTOR: Anna?

203
00:10:34,961 --> 00:10:36,881
How long did you say it'd been
since you'd seen her?

204
00:10:37,121 --> 00:10:38,801
(LIGHT SWITCH FLICKING)

205
00:10:39,321 --> 00:10:41,561
-RYAN: Power's out.
-A few days.

206
00:10:43,561 --> 00:10:45,361
A lot of cobwebs for a few days.

207
00:10:45,441 --> 00:10:48,081
DOCTOR: Yeah,
that's what I was thinking.

208
00:10:48,161 --> 00:10:49,161
Oh.

209
00:10:50,401 --> 00:10:53,321
-Whoa. This is proper weird, now.
-Yeah.

210
00:10:59,641 --> 00:11:01,921
(INHALES DEEPLY)

211
00:11:02,761 --> 00:11:04,161
Graham O'Brien,

212
00:11:05,201 --> 00:11:07,881
what are you doing sniffing coats?

213
00:11:08,561 --> 00:11:09,801
(SNIFFS)

214
00:11:10,361 --> 00:11:12,721
-How's that going to help, eh?
-(THUDDING)

215
00:11:18,321 --> 00:11:20,601
Did Anna ever mention
she had a problem with spiders?

216
00:11:33,121 --> 00:11:34,481
Let's take a look downstairs.

217
00:11:38,961 --> 00:11:40,481
What is that?

218
00:11:42,601 --> 00:11:43,601
Anna?

219
00:11:43,801 --> 00:11:44,841
RYAN: Is she in?

220
00:11:48,881 --> 00:11:50,081
You okay?

221
00:11:54,801 --> 00:11:55,801
Anna?

222
00:11:58,761 --> 00:11:59,881
Oh my days!

223
00:12:00,321 --> 00:12:02,081
(GASPS) My God! Anna!

224
00:12:02,281 --> 00:12:03,281
I'm sorry.

225
00:12:04,441 --> 00:12:05,801
RYAN: Spiders don't do that.

226
00:12:07,041 --> 00:12:08,041
Do they?

227
00:12:08,281 --> 00:12:09,481
Wrong question, Ryan.

228
00:12:09,801 --> 00:12:12,321
You should be asking,
"Where's the spider that did this?"

229
00:12:12,401 --> 00:12:13,641
You think it's still in here?

230
00:12:15,121 --> 00:12:16,321
DOCTOR: Maybe.

231
00:12:25,281 --> 00:12:26,321
Three,

232
00:12:26,881 --> 00:12:27,881
two...

233
00:12:28,601 --> 00:12:29,601
(GASPS)

234
00:12:39,961 --> 00:12:41,441
- (HISSES)
-(RYAN GASPING)

235
00:12:41,521 --> 00:12:43,201
God!

236
00:12:45,081 --> 00:12:46,481
Look at the size of it!

237
00:12:47,361 --> 00:12:49,561
No sudden moves.

238
00:12:51,201 --> 00:12:53,561
JADE: It's domestic,
but it's way too big.

239
00:12:53,681 --> 00:12:55,641
-It's not harmful.
-It suffocated your mate.

240
00:12:55,721 --> 00:12:57,321
Let's put a door between us.
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

241
00:12:57,401 --> 00:12:59,481
When I say "now," quick as you can.

242
00:13:01,201 --> 00:13:02,521
Go, go, go!

243
00:13:02,761 --> 00:13:03,761
-(RYAN GROANING)
-Go!

244
00:13:04,601 --> 00:13:07,121
Ryan, keep it in there. Back in a sec.

245
00:13:07,201 --> 00:13:08,801
We're out. It's contained.

246
00:13:08,921 --> 00:13:11,521
Only a spider, a big spider,
but only a spider.

247
00:13:11,601 --> 00:13:13,281
Not mad keen on spiders.

248
00:13:14,001 --> 00:13:15,241
-Erm...
-What?

249
00:13:16,041 --> 00:13:18,121
-(SKITTERING)
-(SCREAMING)

250
00:13:18,761 --> 00:13:20,841
RYAN: Doctor, it's coming through!

251
00:13:20,921 --> 00:13:23,521
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)
-JADE: We can't keep it in the bedroom.

252
00:13:25,401 --> 00:13:27,761
Rubbish chute.
Maybe that's how it got in.

253
00:13:27,841 --> 00:13:29,041
Could we drive it out through there?

254
00:13:29,121 --> 00:13:30,841
And set it loose across the city? No.

255
00:13:30,921 --> 00:13:33,921
We need to keep it isolated here.
(SIGHS)

256
00:13:34,361 --> 00:13:35,761
Ryan, get up here.

257
00:13:36,761 --> 00:13:38,441
Oi, you just covered me in vinegar.

258
00:13:39,521 --> 00:13:42,921
Spiders' feet are their noses
and they hate the smell of garlic.

259
00:13:43,041 --> 00:13:45,721
And the acetic acid in the vinegar
means it won't come any further.

260
00:13:49,041 --> 00:13:50,641
(CLATTERING)

261
00:13:53,921 --> 00:13:55,361
-Where is it?
-(SPIDER SKITTERING)

262
00:13:55,521 --> 00:13:57,001
-(GASPS)
-(BOTH GASP)

263
00:13:59,801 --> 00:14:01,241
(HISSING)

264
00:14:07,721 --> 00:14:09,921
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

265
00:14:10,401 --> 00:14:12,801
Hi. We don't mean you any harm.

266
00:14:12,881 --> 00:14:14,361
You're not supposed to be this big,

267
00:14:14,441 --> 00:14:16,361
and you're definitely
not supposed to attack humans.

268
00:14:17,081 --> 00:14:19,921
You stay here until I figure this out.

269
00:14:20,801 --> 00:14:22,161
Deal?

270
00:14:29,241 --> 00:14:30,241
Let's go.

271
00:14:30,721 --> 00:14:32,321
Ugh. (PANTING)

272
00:14:33,121 --> 00:14:34,521
RYAN: Oh, I did not like that.

273
00:14:34,761 --> 00:14:36,361
(PANTING)

274
00:14:36,641 --> 00:14:39,121
Jade McIntyre, who are you, exactly?

275
00:14:39,241 --> 00:14:42,241
I saw you check those cobwebs
and you weren't surprised.

276
00:14:42,561 --> 00:14:44,161
Hey! (PANTING)

277
00:14:44,281 --> 00:14:46,521
You'll never guess what I just found
in the loft room.

278
00:14:46,601 --> 00:14:48,761
-It better not be a massive spider.
-Yeah.

279
00:14:48,841 --> 00:14:50,681
Like a big spider, just shed its skin.

280
00:14:50,761 --> 00:14:53,601
A woman has died, and I think you know
more than you're telling.

281
00:14:54,681 --> 00:14:57,441
This isn't the first incident.

282
00:14:58,321 --> 00:15:00,761
Something's happening
with the spiders in this city.

283
00:15:01,321 --> 00:15:02,561
They're out of control.

284
00:15:05,321 --> 00:15:07,521
-(SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE)
-(SIGHS)

285
00:15:08,561 --> 00:15:10,521
Long time to get a parcel.

286
00:15:10,961 --> 00:15:12,761
She always has the weirdest friends.

287
00:15:19,721 --> 00:15:22,641
JADE: The place where Anna worked
with me, it's just over the way.

288
00:15:22,881 --> 00:15:24,761
I'm a research fellow in zoology,

289
00:15:24,881 --> 00:15:26,561
specialising in arachnids
and arthropods,

290
00:15:26,761 --> 00:15:29,481
but spiders are our main focus,

291
00:15:29,561 --> 00:15:32,481
and we're seeing something very wrong
in their behaviour right now.

292
00:15:35,121 --> 00:15:38,281
-How's the house?
-Yeah, fine, yeah.

293
00:15:38,361 --> 00:15:40,761
-Good to be home, eh?
-Yeah.

294
00:15:41,241 --> 00:15:43,761
Look, I found this on the mat.

295
00:15:45,441 --> 00:15:47,001
That's your dad's handwriting, innit?

296
00:15:47,201 --> 00:15:48,761
Looks like it, yeah.

297
00:15:49,881 --> 00:15:51,761
-Well, you're not going to open it?
-No.

298
00:15:53,921 --> 00:15:55,481
(LIGHTS BUZZING)

299
00:16:01,441 --> 00:16:02,521
(DOOR LOCK BEEPING)

300
00:16:10,081 --> 00:16:11,561
FRANKIE: 7his is my insurance policy.

301
00:16:12,321 --> 00:16:15,241
Everything I did
was under strict instruction,

302
00:16:15,321 --> 00:16:18,961
and non-disclosure agreements,
and against my better judgment.

303
00:16:19,241 --> 00:16:22,001
And I hope one day I can forgive myself
for my part in it.

304
00:16:23,521 --> 00:16:24,961
-(BREATHES HEAVILY)
-(SKITTERING)

305
00:16:26,921 --> 00:16:28,041
What's that?

306
00:16:28,641 --> 00:16:30,041
(SPIDER HISSING)

307
00:16:30,121 --> 00:16:31,281
Oh, my God!

308
00:16:31,361 --> 00:16:32,561
(SPIDER SNARLING)

309
00:16:32,881 --> 00:16:35,681
(FRANKIE SCREAMING)

310
00:16:42,161 --> 00:16:43,801
Flippin' heck, Mum.

311
00:16:48,761 --> 00:16:50,641
NAJIA: Quick, get in before anyone sees.

312
00:16:51,321 --> 00:16:53,361
-YASMIN: Hi.
-Oh! (CHUCKLES)

313
00:16:53,561 --> 00:16:57,041
What's the big hug for?
I only saw you this morning!

314
00:16:57,401 --> 00:17:00,281
Yeah, well, it feels longer.

315
00:17:00,361 --> 00:17:01,361
(CHUCKLES)

316
00:17:01,441 --> 00:17:02,961
This is well swanky.

317
00:17:04,321 --> 00:17:06,401
Don't get attached. We need to go.

318
00:17:06,481 --> 00:17:08,481
Can I not have a quick look around?

319
00:17:08,561 --> 00:17:09,561
No, Yaz.

320
00:17:11,121 --> 00:17:12,961
-I've been sacked.
-What?

321
00:17:13,361 --> 00:17:15,801
Mum... But you've just started.

322
00:17:16,121 --> 00:17:19,361
-I know.
-They can't do that. What happened?

323
00:17:19,441 --> 00:17:21,161
-Who sacked you?
-MAN: I did.

324
00:17:21,281 --> 00:17:22,721
Hands in the air, both of you.

325
00:17:23,481 --> 00:17:26,441
As of right now, you're both trespassing
upon my property.

326
00:17:26,521 --> 00:17:29,161
Put the gun down, please, sir.

327
00:17:29,401 --> 00:17:33,321
My hotel, my rules.
You were fired.

328
00:17:33,601 --> 00:17:36,361
Yet, instead of leaving,
you bring someone else in.

329
00:17:36,441 --> 00:17:38,761
She's my daughter
and she's giving me a lift home.

330
00:17:39,161 --> 00:17:42,401
-Oh, how very moving.
-Why'd you fire her?

331
00:17:42,481 --> 00:17:43,881
I don't answer to you.

332
00:17:43,961 --> 00:17:46,321
What are you, 15?
You should be in school!

333
00:17:46,801 --> 00:17:49,961
Your mother isn't supposed to be here.
I told the staff to take two days off.

334
00:17:50,041 --> 00:17:52,761
I came in to do extra preparation
before we opened.

335
00:17:52,841 --> 00:17:55,121
Well, I really don't care,

336
00:17:55,241 --> 00:17:57,961
because if I hadn't fired you then,
I would have fired you 10 minutes ago

337
00:17:58,041 --> 00:18:00,001
when I saw the rooms. Disgraceful!

338
00:18:00,641 --> 00:18:02,361
What rooms? I don't understand.

339
00:18:02,441 --> 00:18:03,841
I'm sure you don't understand.

340
00:18:03,921 --> 00:18:06,721
Would you like to see how good
your mother really isn't?

341
00:18:08,721 --> 00:18:10,881
JADE: We reckon there could be around
21 quadrillion spiders

342
00:18:10,961 --> 00:18:12,121
on the planet in total.

343
00:18:12,281 --> 00:18:13,961
So what sort of research
are you doing in here?

344
00:18:14,041 --> 00:18:17,041
We're interested in utilising
the genetic strengths of arachnids.

345
00:18:17,361 --> 00:18:20,521
Ordinary spider silk is as strong
as steel, or as tough as Kevlar.

346
00:18:20,641 --> 00:18:21,921
GRAHAM: Still don't make me like 'em.

347
00:18:22,001 --> 00:18:23,121
DOCTOR: Ooh, fun fact.

348
00:18:23,241 --> 00:18:25,841
If you weave drag line spider silk
as thick as a pencil,

349
00:18:25,921 --> 00:18:27,401
it's strong enough
to stop a plane in flight.

350
00:18:27,601 --> 00:18:29,121
-Mmm?
-You're kidding!

351
00:18:29,241 --> 00:18:31,441
I'm not. I've had to deal with it.

352
00:18:31,721 --> 00:18:33,841
Well, me and Amelia Earheart.

353
00:18:34,201 --> 00:18:35,401
You'd like her. She's a right laugh.

354
00:18:36,401 --> 00:18:38,641
So, what else are you doing in here?

355
00:18:39,041 --> 00:18:42,081
I've been working on an enzyme
to increase their lifespan.

356
00:18:42,641 --> 00:18:45,081
Spiders can keep growing
for as long as they live.

357
00:18:45,161 --> 00:18:47,921
That spider in Anna's flat was way
bigger than a normal household spider.

358
00:18:48,001 --> 00:18:49,001
-JADE: Yeah.
-Did Anna

359
00:18:49,081 --> 00:18:51,201
-have access to your experiments?
-JADE: No!

360
00:18:51,441 --> 00:18:52,961
She was on the admin team.

361
00:18:53,041 --> 00:18:54,761
Everything we do here is secure.

362
00:18:55,161 --> 00:18:58,521
We discard all carcasses responsibly
through a specialist company.

363
00:18:59,001 --> 00:19:01,681
Unless she was taking things
without us knowing,

364
00:19:02,521 --> 00:19:03,921
but she's not that kind of person.

365
00:19:05,321 --> 00:19:06,681
I should notify the police.

366
00:19:07,561 --> 00:19:09,481
What is it you wanted to show us?

367
00:19:09,681 --> 00:19:13,361
Reports of unusual spider activity
in Sheffield over the last three months.

368
00:19:13,761 --> 00:19:17,681
From the police, pest controllers
and to us, here.

369
00:19:17,761 --> 00:19:20,481
Rare sightings, an increase in numbers,

370
00:19:20,561 --> 00:19:22,481
spiders you don't normally see
at this time of year.

371
00:19:22,561 --> 00:19:26,001
(GASPS) Something's wrong with the
spider ecosystem in South Yorkshire.

372
00:19:26,161 --> 00:19:28,761
Exactly, but we don't know what.

373
00:19:29,081 --> 00:19:30,161
They have nothing in common.

374
00:19:30,241 --> 00:19:32,481
Different species, different quantities.

375
00:19:32,841 --> 00:19:36,601
Some are large massings, some have been
a profusion of web-building.

376
00:19:36,681 --> 00:19:41,641
I can't work out if they're confused,
angry, or scared.

377
00:19:42,441 --> 00:19:44,081
Or trying to send a message.

378
00:19:49,001 --> 00:19:50,121
What are you doing?

379
00:19:55,401 --> 00:19:56,401
(GASPS)

380
00:19:57,841 --> 00:19:58,841
DOCTOR: Where's that?

381
00:20:01,321 --> 00:20:02,801
Now, if you're so great,

382
00:20:02,881 --> 00:20:04,641
-explain this.
-(DOOR CLOSES)

383
00:20:04,721 --> 00:20:06,161
-Hmm?
-(GASPS)

384
00:20:06,281 --> 00:20:08,641
I can't... That's not possible.

385
00:20:08,721 --> 00:20:10,321
You're fired. Again.

386
00:20:10,801 --> 00:20:12,041
(SMART WATCH BEEPS)

387
00:20:12,561 --> 00:20:15,441
Oh, it's time for my scheduled
bathroom break.

388
00:20:15,601 --> 00:20:17,601
Kevin, we'll go next door.

389
00:20:18,241 --> 00:20:22,481
And, when I'm done,
Kevin will escort you off the grounds.

390
00:20:22,561 --> 00:20:23,561
Forever.

391
00:20:23,721 --> 00:20:24,721
(DOOR OPENS)

392
00:20:25,161 --> 00:20:26,921
YASMIN: Scheduled bathroom breaks?

393
00:20:27,121 --> 00:20:29,081
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-I checked this room yesterday,

394
00:20:29,161 --> 00:20:30,361
it wasn't like this.

395
00:20:30,801 --> 00:20:33,641
(SKITTERING)

396
00:20:34,841 --> 00:20:36,161
Did you hear that?

397
00:20:37,161 --> 00:20:38,161
Yeah.

398
00:20:50,721 --> 00:20:52,361
(SKITTERING)

399
00:21:02,401 --> 00:21:04,361
(MOBILE RINGING)

400
00:21:07,681 --> 00:21:09,281
-(MOBILE BEEPS)
-Hello?

401
00:21:11,161 --> 00:21:13,281
Yeah. It's for you.

402
00:21:13,561 --> 00:21:14,801
It's a doctor.

403
00:21:16,401 --> 00:21:18,721
Hi, Doctor.
You're never gonna believe it.

404
00:21:18,881 --> 00:21:20,521
Are you at the hotel
where your mum works?

405
00:21:20,641 --> 00:21:22,401
-YASMIN: (ON PHONE) Yeah.
-Can you let us in?

406
00:21:22,721 --> 00:21:24,441
Frankie, where are you?

407
00:21:25,041 --> 00:21:26,601
Don't keep me waiting. (SIGHS)

408
00:21:28,161 --> 00:21:30,481
(WATER RUNNING)

409
00:21:37,241 --> 00:21:38,601
(THUDDING IN PIPES)

410
00:21:43,481 --> 00:21:45,201
(THUDDING CONTINUES)

411
00:21:52,001 --> 00:21:53,241
(THUDDING CONTINUES)

412
00:21:56,881 --> 00:21:57,921
(SLITHERING)

413
00:22:01,361 --> 00:22:02,561
(TUB CRACKING)

414
00:22:06,681 --> 00:22:08,361
(TUB SHATTERING)

415
00:22:13,561 --> 00:22:14,561
(GROANS)

416
00:22:14,641 --> 00:22:15,641
(COUGHS)

417
00:22:16,041 --> 00:22:17,041
(GASPS)

418
00:22:17,161 --> 00:22:18,201
(SNARLS)

419
00:22:19,961 --> 00:22:21,121
(SCREAMING)

420
00:22:23,481 --> 00:22:25,241
Kevin! Kevin! (GASPS)

421
00:22:25,681 --> 00:22:27,081
Oh, my God!

422
00:22:27,801 --> 00:22:29,561
(SPIDER HISSING)

423
00:22:30,121 --> 00:22:31,721
(KEVIN SCREAMING)

424
00:22:32,121 --> 00:22:34,521
KEVIN: Get it off me! Help!

425
00:22:34,641 --> 00:22:36,361
(KEVIN CONTINUES SCREAMING)

426
00:22:36,921 --> 00:22:39,001
Hi! Yaz's mum.

427
00:22:39,161 --> 00:22:40,961
-(BREATHING HEAVILY)
-Najia.

428
00:22:41,241 --> 00:22:42,481
Yaz, they can't be here.

429
00:22:42,561 --> 00:22:45,441
Najia, you made a very awesome human.
Tell me what's going on.

430
00:22:45,521 --> 00:22:46,561
-(KEVIN SCREAMING)
-(GUNSHOTS)

431
00:22:47,001 --> 00:22:48,801
-Was that gunshots?
-Come on.

432
00:22:49,161 --> 00:22:50,161
-Kevin!
-(GUNSHOT)

433
00:22:50,241 --> 00:22:51,241
(THUDDING BEHIND DOOR)

434
00:22:52,001 --> 00:22:53,321
Is it dead?

435
00:22:54,841 --> 00:22:56,161
Kevin?

436
00:23:03,961 --> 00:23:04,961
(GASPS)

437
00:23:08,081 --> 00:23:09,201
(MOUTHING) Oh, God!

438
00:23:10,801 --> 00:23:12,281
Oh, my God!

439
00:23:12,921 --> 00:23:13,961
He got Kevin.

440
00:23:14,961 --> 00:23:16,841
I have no more Kevin.

441
00:23:18,321 --> 00:23:19,761
I'm compromised.

442
00:23:19,881 --> 00:23:22,321
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

443
00:23:24,041 --> 00:23:25,041
(GASPS)

444
00:23:25,161 --> 00:23:27,041
Oh, no, my cell!

445
00:23:27,841 --> 00:23:30,321
(KEVIN GROANING)

446
00:23:32,601 --> 00:23:33,761
(GASPS)

447
00:23:33,841 --> 00:23:35,641
KEVIN: Help me! Help me!

448
00:23:35,961 --> 00:23:39,001
(KEVIN SCREAMING)

449
00:23:40,081 --> 00:23:41,481
(SCREAMING)

450
00:23:44,601 --> 00:23:46,401
(PANTING)

451
00:23:46,681 --> 00:23:48,441
GRAHAM: You are joking!

452
00:23:49,001 --> 00:23:51,001
-No way.
-Oh, no.

453
00:23:52,601 --> 00:23:53,801
-Crisis investigators.
-(GASPS)

454
00:23:53,881 --> 00:23:56,001
You just ran really quickly
out of a room looking really scared.

455
00:23:56,081 --> 00:23:57,401
Tell me exactly what's going on,

456
00:23:57,481 --> 00:23:59,521
omitting no detail,
no matter how strange.

457
00:23:59,601 --> 00:24:01,761
A giant spider just smashed
through my bathtub

458
00:24:01,841 --> 00:24:03,681
and took out my bodyguard Kevin.

459
00:24:04,881 --> 00:24:06,321
Right.

460
00:24:06,401 --> 00:24:07,961
Very succinct summary.
Well done.

461
00:24:08,481 --> 00:24:10,921
You just wait here with my people.

462
00:24:12,281 --> 00:24:13,601
Spider smashed through a bath.

463
00:24:14,441 --> 00:24:16,401
(BREATHING HEAVILY) Right.

464
00:24:17,321 --> 00:24:18,481
(DOOR OPENS)

465
00:24:20,801 --> 00:24:22,761
-(DOOR CLOSES)
-(SIGHS)

466
00:24:25,121 --> 00:24:26,121
Hey.

467
00:24:26,521 --> 00:24:27,521
Hey.

468
00:24:29,081 --> 00:24:30,201
You're that bloke.

469
00:24:30,361 --> 00:24:32,321
(INHALES SHARPLY) Yeah.

470
00:24:33,161 --> 00:24:34,561
-(LAUGHING)
-All right.

471
00:24:44,481 --> 00:24:46,241
The room next door
is covered in cobwebs.

472
00:24:46,841 --> 00:24:48,721
-Top to bottom.
-Just like your neighbour's house.

473
00:24:48,881 --> 00:24:50,441
-What?
-Big spider problem

474
00:24:50,521 --> 00:24:53,041
in this city right now, Yaz.
Glad to be home?

475
00:24:55,761 --> 00:24:57,561
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

476
00:24:58,361 --> 00:25:00,561
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER BEEPS)

477
00:25:09,601 --> 00:25:12,201
(PANTING)

478
00:25:16,921 --> 00:25:18,641
(SKITTERING)

479
00:25:21,841 --> 00:25:23,161
Hi.

480
00:25:24,561 --> 00:25:25,641
(HISSES)

481
00:25:25,881 --> 00:25:27,321
Looking for a Kevin.

482
00:25:29,441 --> 00:25:30,681
-See it?
-Really close.

483
00:25:31,601 --> 00:25:33,001
(BOTH PANTING)

484
00:25:34,281 --> 00:25:36,081
MAN: Did you see it? Did you find him?

485
00:25:36,241 --> 00:25:37,881
-(PANTING)
-Where's Kevin?

486
00:25:38,041 --> 00:25:40,801
We need to move out of this area, quick.
It's too dark, too deserted.

487
00:25:40,881 --> 00:25:41,881
Spiders love that.

488
00:25:41,961 --> 00:25:43,521
We need to go somewhere bright and busy.

489
00:25:43,601 --> 00:25:47,161
No, no, no. No, we need to get
as far away from that thing as possible.

490
00:25:47,241 --> 00:25:48,881
-I'm with him.
-I know the way out.

491
00:25:49,161 --> 00:25:51,481
-Everyone, follow Yaz's mum.
-NAJIA: It's Najia.

492
00:25:51,881 --> 00:25:53,521
Wait!

493
00:25:53,601 --> 00:25:55,641
-Who are you people?
-Word of advice, mate.

494
00:25:55,721 --> 00:25:57,001
Run now, ask questions later.

495
00:25:57,521 --> 00:25:58,521
(ALL BREATHING HEAVILY)

496
00:25:58,921 --> 00:26:00,041
RYAN: Oh, that's bad.

497
00:26:00,401 --> 00:26:01,401
Oh.

498
00:26:04,761 --> 00:26:06,121
YASMIN: We just came in that way.

499
00:26:06,201 --> 00:26:07,801
How have they done so many webs so fast?

500
00:26:07,881 --> 00:26:09,641
GRAHAM: Never mind that,
let's just get through 'em.

501
00:26:09,721 --> 00:26:11,561
No, this can't be happening.

502
00:26:11,721 --> 00:26:15,201
This is a protest.
One of those eco-protests, huh?

503
00:26:15,321 --> 00:26:17,321
This isn't spiders.
Spiders can't do that.

504
00:26:17,401 --> 00:26:20,241
These spiders can.
Those aren't normal cobwebs.

505
00:26:20,321 --> 00:26:23,281
They know we're here,
and they're trying to seal us in.

506
00:26:23,441 --> 00:26:26,401
They're trying to make the whole hotel
their web.

507
00:26:26,601 --> 00:26:28,641
And we're the flies.

508
00:26:28,721 --> 00:26:29,761
We're not leaving.

509
00:26:29,841 --> 00:26:33,881
We have to find out why they're here
and stop them getting any further.

510
00:26:34,081 --> 00:26:36,361
We need to find a safe haven. Yaz's mum?

511
00:26:36,601 --> 00:26:37,681
Kitchen?

512
00:26:37,841 --> 00:26:39,161
DOCTOR: Lead on.

513
00:26:40,081 --> 00:26:42,361
(PANTING) Good. This will do.

514
00:26:42,441 --> 00:26:45,841
Okay, thinking. Need to be quick.
Spiders move in fast.

515
00:26:46,081 --> 00:26:48,921
Why is this hotel the epicentre
of spider activity?

516
00:26:49,081 --> 00:26:50,521
Wait!

517
00:26:50,641 --> 00:26:54,161
Nobody talk until you tell me
what you're all doing here!

518
00:26:54,681 --> 00:26:56,801
(BREATHING HEAVILY) "Spiders"?

519
00:26:57,681 --> 00:26:58,921
-Plural?
-Very plural.

520
00:26:59,041 --> 00:27:00,441
Sorry, I don't know who you are.

521
00:27:00,521 --> 00:27:01,721
Oh! (SCOFFS) Really?

522
00:27:01,801 --> 00:27:04,441
Because you must be the only person
on the planet that doesn't.

523
00:27:04,521 --> 00:27:06,321
Are you Ed Sheeran? Is he Ed Sheeran?

524
00:27:06,401 --> 00:27:08,641
Everyone talks about Ed Sheeran
round about now, don't they?

525
00:27:08,801 --> 00:27:12,641
I am not Ed Sheeran, I am Jack Robertson
and this is my hotel.

526
00:27:12,761 --> 00:27:17,081
Just one hotel in an incredibly
successful chain of hotels,

527
00:27:17,241 --> 00:27:20,401
which is just one small part
of my business portfolio

528
00:27:20,481 --> 00:27:22,641
as featured in Fortune Global 500.

529
00:27:22,721 --> 00:27:24,201
Does that ring a bell?

530
00:27:24,361 --> 00:27:26,201
Should I look impressed right now?
Is that impressive?

531
00:27:26,281 --> 00:27:28,201
He's running for President in 2020.

532
00:27:28,321 --> 00:27:31,321
-Ed Sheeran?
-No, him. Robertson. Aren't you?

533
00:27:31,401 --> 00:27:33,361
Well, I haven't declared
my intentions yet.

534
00:27:33,441 --> 00:27:35,801
But, look, we're talking about spiders.

535
00:27:35,921 --> 00:27:38,081
See? Typical politician,
avoiding the question.

536
00:27:38,161 --> 00:27:40,161
I am not a politician,
I'm a businessman

537
00:27:40,241 --> 00:27:41,561
and I know how to run things.

538
00:27:41,641 --> 00:27:44,561
I've heard you're only running because
you've hated Trump for decades.

539
00:27:44,641 --> 00:27:47,201
Please don't mention that name.
(INHALES SHARPLY)

540
00:27:47,321 --> 00:27:51,721
Look, I was just attacked by a spider
the size of a bathtub

541
00:27:51,801 --> 00:27:55,801
-and it's all her fault!
-I told you, I know nothing about this.

542
00:27:55,881 --> 00:27:58,041
Mum, don't even talk to him,
he fired you.

543
00:27:58,121 --> 00:27:59,281
What? He didn't!

544
00:27:59,361 --> 00:28:02,081
You didn't! You can't be President
if you fire Yaz's mum.

545
00:28:02,161 --> 00:28:03,561
-Najia.
-I hate spiders.

546
00:28:03,801 --> 00:28:05,881
-Phobia-hate.
-RYAN: Oh, man. Me too.

547
00:28:06,161 --> 00:28:07,921
And there's loads of them
knocking about right now.

548
00:28:08,081 --> 00:28:10,481
I will not have them in my hotel.

549
00:28:10,561 --> 00:28:12,161
I mean, you're running for President,

550
00:28:12,281 --> 00:28:14,881
it could be espionage, you know,
targeted directly...

551
00:28:15,041 --> 00:28:16,721
At you by Russians!

552
00:28:16,801 --> 00:28:19,561
That's possible. There are a lot of
people that would like to see me dead.

553
00:28:19,641 --> 00:28:21,001
-Funny that.
-See?

554
00:28:21,081 --> 00:28:22,761
They don't need giant spiders,

555
00:28:22,841 --> 00:28:24,561
they'd just pop a tiny poisonous one
on your pillow.

556
00:28:24,641 --> 00:28:27,841
You've really got to stop
saying stuff like that.

557
00:28:28,041 --> 00:28:30,161
-So, what do we do?
-Why are you asking her?

558
00:28:30,281 --> 00:28:32,321
-'Cause she's in charge, bro.
-ROBERTSON: Says who?

559
00:28:32,441 --> 00:28:33,561
ALL: Says us!

560
00:28:33,681 --> 00:28:34,961
NAJIA: How do you all know each other?

561
00:28:35,121 --> 00:28:36,921
Mum, can you shut up a second?

562
00:28:37,001 --> 00:28:38,441
Right, we need two things.

563
00:28:38,561 --> 00:28:40,681
Plans of the hotel and a captive spider.

564
00:28:44,841 --> 00:28:46,881
I'm not getting near the spider.

565
00:28:50,601 --> 00:28:52,761
GRAHAM: I really don't like this.

566
00:28:52,841 --> 00:28:54,641
I don't want to do this.

567
00:28:54,721 --> 00:28:57,921
(SIGHS) I can't stand it.
Come on, Graham, deep breaths now.

568
00:28:58,001 --> 00:28:59,561
(EXHALES SHARPLY)

569
00:29:05,001 --> 00:29:06,761
Sorry, mate, don't mind me.

570
00:29:09,761 --> 00:29:11,521
No, no, go on. You carry on.

571
00:29:11,881 --> 00:29:13,801
Stay away. Go on, stay away.

572
00:29:14,001 --> 00:29:15,281
Nothin' to see here.

573
00:29:15,521 --> 00:29:16,681
I'm warnin' ya.

574
00:29:17,841 --> 00:29:18,921
Go on, get away!

575
00:29:19,321 --> 00:29:21,761
Ooh, I've got ya! (LAUGHING)

576
00:29:21,961 --> 00:29:23,041
You took your time!

577
00:29:23,201 --> 00:29:26,641
-One, two, three, lift it!
-Ooh! (BREATHING HEAVILY)

578
00:29:27,441 --> 00:29:28,481
-Graham!
-What?

579
00:29:28,561 --> 00:29:30,041
-RYAN: Behind you!
-All right! Leg it!

580
00:29:30,241 --> 00:29:32,241
-(RYAN GASPING)
-Faster, come on!

581
00:29:36,281 --> 00:29:38,601
Now, hotel plans. Let's see.

582
00:29:40,561 --> 00:29:43,641
That can't be accurate, it doesn't even
have my panic room marked on it.

583
00:29:45,481 --> 00:29:47,961
Any issues with spiders
before today, Najia,

584
00:29:48,041 --> 00:29:50,241
-here or at home?
-My home?

585
00:29:50,321 --> 00:29:51,881
One of your neighbours
had a spider problem.

586
00:29:51,961 --> 00:29:53,921
The link between both places is you.

587
00:29:54,081 --> 00:29:58,841
I knew it, and I'm going to litigate you
until your last breath, Nah-dia.

588
00:29:59,041 --> 00:30:01,161
It's Najia, and I've done nothing.

589
00:30:01,281 --> 00:30:04,561
-Are you sure?
-NAJIA: Sorry, but who are you?

590
00:30:04,641 --> 00:30:07,121
How do you know my daughter?
Why haven't I met you before?

591
00:30:07,201 --> 00:30:08,201
Oh, not now.

592
00:30:08,281 --> 00:30:10,641
Oh, yes, now.
It's not a difficult question.

593
00:30:10,721 --> 00:30:13,521
-It is a bit of a long answer.
-Well, I've got time.

594
00:30:13,881 --> 00:30:16,281
But I haven't. Not right now.

595
00:30:18,441 --> 00:30:20,001
Are you two seeing each other?

596
00:30:20,201 --> 00:30:21,881
(SCOFFS)

597
00:30:22,281 --> 00:30:24,401
I don't think so. Are we?

598
00:30:25,561 --> 00:30:27,601
-We're friends!
-Mmm.

599
00:30:27,681 --> 00:30:30,721
I owe the Doctor my life,
quite a few times over.

600
00:30:30,801 --> 00:30:32,161
What is that even supposed to mean?

601
00:30:32,281 --> 00:30:34,961
Please, can we not have
this conversation now?

602
00:30:35,081 --> 00:30:36,241
And not in front of him.

603
00:30:36,321 --> 00:30:37,881
Oh, I'm enjoying this.

604
00:30:38,001 --> 00:30:40,401
How long did it take you
to build this hotel?

605
00:30:40,481 --> 00:30:41,961
ROBERTSON: Five years.

606
00:30:42,161 --> 00:30:45,201
We have 15 of these hotels
throughout the world now.

607
00:30:45,281 --> 00:30:49,721
Repurposing former industrial sites
into luxury leisure venues.

608
00:30:49,921 --> 00:30:52,201
Repurposing?
What was the site before?

609
00:30:52,681 --> 00:30:54,681
I don't have...

610
00:30:54,761 --> 00:30:56,161
Clarity on that.

611
00:30:56,681 --> 00:30:57,681
I do.

612
00:30:59,681 --> 00:31:02,161
Coal mines. This was mining land.

613
00:31:05,361 --> 00:31:06,561
JADE: That's not good.

614
00:31:06,641 --> 00:31:08,481
GRAHAM: You're telling me,
I can't stand 'em.

615
00:31:08,561 --> 00:31:11,161
-JADE: No, I've seen these before.
-(GRAHAM GROANS)

616
00:31:11,241 --> 00:31:12,921
Was that the largest one out there?

617
00:31:13,001 --> 00:31:15,561
Well, we're... We're not going to go
and double-check, are we?

618
00:31:15,641 --> 00:31:17,001
Are we?

619
00:31:18,241 --> 00:31:21,241
I'm afraid I'm going to need you
to do exactly that

620
00:31:22,001 --> 00:31:23,681
while I find the others.

621
00:31:26,521 --> 00:31:28,401
We've just passed the entrance
to the back of the spa.

622
00:31:28,481 --> 00:31:29,681
We should be here now.

623
00:31:29,761 --> 00:31:31,641
You're not going down there.
It's too dangerous.

624
00:31:31,761 --> 00:31:33,561
I eat danger for breakfast.

625
00:31:33,681 --> 00:31:36,081
I don't, I prefer cereal.
Or croissants.

626
00:31:36,361 --> 00:31:38,521
Or those little fried Portuguese...

627
00:31:38,641 --> 00:31:40,441
Never mind, it's not important.

628
00:31:42,081 --> 00:31:43,361
Ha! See?

629
00:31:44,721 --> 00:31:47,081
Look at this!
"Keep out, danger of death.”

630
00:31:47,161 --> 00:31:48,801
You are not authorised
to go in here!

631
00:31:48,881 --> 00:31:51,521
Dude, I've all the authorisation
I ever need.

632
00:31:51,721 --> 00:31:53,081
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

633
00:31:53,201 --> 00:31:54,641
I call people "dude” now.

634
00:31:55,001 --> 00:31:56,761
Doctor, I need to speak to you.

635
00:31:56,881 --> 00:31:58,121
We need to do it as we walk.

636
00:31:58,201 --> 00:32:00,761
There's something behind this door
people want to keep locked away.

637
00:32:00,841 --> 00:32:02,641
Oh, sure, it's a party.
Everybody can come.

638
00:32:02,761 --> 00:32:03,761
Thanks.

639
00:32:03,841 --> 00:32:05,601
Doctor, I've seen these spiders before.

640
00:32:06,201 --> 00:32:08,321
-But you.
-You're not the boss of me any more.

641
00:32:10,761 --> 00:32:12,121
(SIGHS)

642
00:32:12,761 --> 00:32:13,761
(DOOR BOLT LOCKING)

643
00:32:14,841 --> 00:32:15,921
DOCTOR: Nice work, Yaz.

644
00:32:16,041 --> 00:32:18,521
ROBERTSON: No, not nice work.
None of you are allowed down here.

645
00:32:18,601 --> 00:32:21,081
Are all your hotels built
on repurposed sites?

646
00:32:21,161 --> 00:32:22,721
ROBERTSON: Well, that's the business!

647
00:32:22,801 --> 00:32:25,601
I mean, every city in the world,
big or small,

648
00:32:25,681 --> 00:32:27,561
has an area that they want repurposed.

649
00:32:27,721 --> 00:32:30,201
Maybe it's not too pretty.
Maybe it's never been used.

650
00:32:30,281 --> 00:32:32,001
Maybe it's an industry that's died.

651
00:32:32,081 --> 00:32:33,921
We go in and we help them figure it out.

652
00:32:34,081 --> 00:32:35,641
We get a good deal,

653
00:32:35,841 --> 00:32:38,841
but we give them world-class facilities.

654
00:32:38,921 --> 00:32:40,681
It's a win for everybody!

655
00:32:40,761 --> 00:32:41,921
A network of mining tunnels

656
00:32:42,001 --> 00:32:43,681
could explain how the bigger spiders
are moving.

657
00:32:43,761 --> 00:32:45,921
The question is,
does that make your hotel

658
00:32:46,001 --> 00:32:48,241
their target or their base?

659
00:32:48,321 --> 00:32:50,361
What is that smell?

660
00:32:54,681 --> 00:32:56,481
What are they?

661
00:32:58,321 --> 00:32:59,921
Oh, my God.

662
00:33:00,601 --> 00:33:02,241
You guys, stay back.

663
00:33:03,521 --> 00:33:05,161
Keep an eye out for me.

664
00:33:09,281 --> 00:33:11,201
(BREATHING HEAVILY)

665
00:33:13,521 --> 00:33:14,801
(SIGHS)

666
00:33:16,641 --> 00:33:17,841
(STRAINING)

667
00:33:20,361 --> 00:33:21,641
ROBERTSON: Oh, my God.

668
00:33:23,241 --> 00:33:24,881
Do you know who this is?

669
00:33:26,041 --> 00:33:30,361
Her name is Frankie.
Look what they did to her!

670
00:33:30,481 --> 00:33:32,001
Why are they in cocoons?

671
00:33:32,161 --> 00:33:34,041
I think they're being stored as food.

672
00:33:34,121 --> 00:33:35,641
Spiders don't eat people.

673
00:33:35,801 --> 00:33:37,881
DOCTOR: I said they're being stored.
They haven't eaten them.

674
00:33:37,961 --> 00:33:40,241
They're out sized and confused.

675
00:33:40,321 --> 00:33:42,761
All their behavioural patterns
have been disrupted.

676
00:33:42,841 --> 00:33:44,281
How did they get like this?

677
00:33:44,361 --> 00:33:46,121
JADE: It doesn't make any sense.

678
00:33:46,281 --> 00:33:48,481
This is not what spiders do.

679
00:33:51,361 --> 00:33:52,881
(STRAINING)

680
00:33:56,081 --> 00:33:58,761
DOCTOR: I presume this is Kevin.
ROBERTSON: Yeah.

681
00:34:00,401 --> 00:34:02,081
YASMIN: Doctor.

682
00:34:03,401 --> 00:34:05,481
ROBERTSON: You don't need
to go any deeper!

683
00:34:05,681 --> 00:34:07,441
-What is it?
-Look.

684
00:34:09,441 --> 00:34:11,161
(SIGHS)

685
00:34:15,521 --> 00:34:17,161
YASMIN: Have you seen what's down here?

686
00:34:18,561 --> 00:34:20,121
It's landfill.

687
00:34:20,481 --> 00:34:22,561
-Is that what the smell is?
-(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

688
00:34:22,641 --> 00:34:24,281
It goes on for miles.

689
00:34:24,761 --> 00:34:25,801
And down.

690
00:34:26,121 --> 00:34:27,801
Your hotel's built on landfill?

691
00:34:27,961 --> 00:34:30,161
I have a lot of companies, okay?

692
00:34:30,321 --> 00:34:33,361
Er, JLR does corporate waste disposal.

693
00:34:33,441 --> 00:34:37,481
Very efficient, very highly-rated
internationally.

694
00:34:37,561 --> 00:34:41,401
You fill up disused mines with landfill
waste and build a luxury hotel on top.

695
00:34:41,521 --> 00:34:45,001
Smart business planning.
Perfect vertical integration.

696
00:34:45,081 --> 00:34:46,481
NAJIA: All your hotels
are built this way?

697
00:34:46,561 --> 00:34:48,041
Not quite perfect, I'm afraid.

698
00:34:48,121 --> 00:34:49,281
Not quite efficient.

699
00:34:49,401 --> 00:34:51,081
A blocked-in site pumping out

700
00:34:51,201 --> 00:34:53,481
methane and sulphides
and trichloroethylene.

701
00:34:53,601 --> 00:34:57,201
Never mind the specialist material
that hasn't been properly preserved.

702
00:34:57,281 --> 00:35:01,641
A soup of toxic waste,
incredibly badly managed.

703
00:35:01,721 --> 00:35:05,521
I mean, there's no outlet for it.
It's just building and marinading

704
00:35:05,601 --> 00:35:07,521
and becoming more and more toxic.

705
00:35:07,961 --> 00:35:10,761
-It's a botched job!
-I didn't know.

706
00:35:10,881 --> 00:35:12,361
NAJIA: Yes, you did.

707
00:35:12,481 --> 00:35:14,641
That's what she was telling you
when I saw you.

708
00:35:14,721 --> 00:35:15,921
-That woman Frankie.
-(SCOFFS)

709
00:35:16,041 --> 00:35:18,161
She was telling you
this site is unsafe.

710
00:35:18,721 --> 00:35:23,201
Okay, all right. You're right.
That's why I came here.

711
00:35:23,401 --> 00:35:27,801
Apparently JLR was a little overzealous
in cutting corners

712
00:35:27,881 --> 00:35:30,041
and worried about
keeping the bottom line

713
00:35:30,121 --> 00:35:31,521
instead of doing the right thing.

714
00:35:31,601 --> 00:35:34,641
But I just sign the contracts, okay?

715
00:35:35,081 --> 00:35:37,281
I expect other people to do their jobs.

716
00:35:37,361 --> 00:35:39,521
-This is not on me.
-Don't you even care?

717
00:35:39,641 --> 00:35:42,641
Look, I'm going to pay you all off.
You'll never have to work again.

718
00:35:42,761 --> 00:35:45,121
I like working.
Do you know the worst thing?

719
00:35:45,641 --> 00:35:47,841
Bits of this
is leaking out above here.

720
00:35:47,921 --> 00:35:52,041
It's in my kitchen.
My husband's right, it's a conspiracy.

721
00:35:52,121 --> 00:35:54,961
Do you have any idea how annoying it is
when my husband's right?

722
00:35:55,041 --> 00:35:57,321
Look, I've never even been down here.

723
00:35:57,441 --> 00:35:58,921
It doesn't even add up.

724
00:35:59,641 --> 00:36:01,321
It does for me.

725
00:36:01,481 --> 00:36:04,881
JLR Disposal.
JLR takes the waste from our lab.

726
00:36:05,441 --> 00:36:08,281
Our aborted experiments
and our spider carcasses.

727
00:36:08,401 --> 00:36:10,521
And they're all in there.

728
00:36:10,641 --> 00:36:12,641
Your spider carcasses
in his toxic waste!

729
00:36:12,721 --> 00:36:15,521
Not my fault! I didn't know anything
about spider carcasses.

730
00:36:15,601 --> 00:36:18,121
Of course you didn't!
You don't know anything.

731
00:36:18,241 --> 00:36:20,641
You just avoid
taking any responsibility.

732
00:36:21,601 --> 00:36:23,921
I'm running through our work,
stuff we shut down.

733
00:36:24,121 --> 00:36:28,041
Spiders bio engineered for stronger
cobwebs, prolonged life.

734
00:36:28,241 --> 00:36:31,881
Because spiders can keep growing
as long as they live.

735
00:36:32,081 --> 00:36:35,121
What if our waste included something
that we thought was dead,

736
00:36:35,201 --> 00:36:37,121
but was still just alive?

737
00:36:37,241 --> 00:36:40,041
And with enough food
in all that waste to survive,

738
00:36:40,121 --> 00:36:42,641
and enough toxicity to mutate

739
00:36:42,721 --> 00:36:45,641
and to keep on growing.

740
00:36:54,401 --> 00:36:55,561
(DOOR CREAKING)

741
00:36:55,641 --> 00:36:58,241
GRAHAM: I don't know what she expects
us to bring back.

742
00:36:58,361 --> 00:36:59,801
-Graham?
-Mmm-hmm?

743
00:37:00,561 --> 00:37:01,761
I've read the letter.

744
00:37:03,441 --> 00:37:05,201
-Oh. Huh.
-From my dad.

745
00:37:09,241 --> 00:37:10,841
He said he's sorry for not being there.

746
00:37:11,721 --> 00:37:14,201
For me. For us.

747
00:37:15,241 --> 00:37:16,521
For Nan.

748
00:37:18,801 --> 00:37:21,281
-Yeah?
-He wants us to reconnect.

749
00:37:23,121 --> 00:37:26,801
